Handling Outliers¶

In [106]:
z_scores = np.abs((df - df.mean()) / df.std())
threshold = 3
outlier_indices = np.where(z_scores > threshold)
print("Indices of Rows with Outliers:", outlier_indices)

Indices of Rows with Outliers: (array([ 169,  229,  300,  372,  584, 1549], dtype=int64), array([4, 4, 4, 4, 4, 4], dtype=int64))
In [107]:
indices_result = (np.array([  95,  226,  305, 1387, 1406, 1416, 1554, 1693, 1705, 1880, 1882, 1888]),
                  np.array([4, 4, 4, 4, 4, 4, 4, 4, 4, 4, 4, 4]))

indices_df = pd.DataFrame({'Row_Index': indices_result[0], 'Column_Index': indices_result[1]})

print(indices_df)

    Row_Index  Column_Index

The table above shows the outliers in the whole dataset , and the results show that there is a 12 data point considered to be an outlier and these data points id from the column of "fc" (Front Camera).¶

In [ ]:

So, we need to handle these outliers,¶

there is 2 ways to do this , either removing the rows where these outliers are located or by replacing the outliers with the value of the mean of their corresponding column.¶

i will go with the second approach where it seems to be a better handling method; because deleting rows may cause a loss of information for the model.¶

In [110]:
for row_index, col_index in zip(*outlier_indices):
    column_mean = df.iloc[:, col_index].mean()
    df.iat[row_index, col_index] = column_mean

Checking for imbalanced data¶

In [108]:
for column in df.columns:
    value_counts = df[column].value_counts()
    imbalance_ratio = value_counts.max() / value_counts.min()
In [109]:
imbalance_threshold = 0.2

if imbalance_ratio < 1 - imbalance_threshold:
    print(f"Column '{column}' has imbalanced data. Imbalance ratio: {imbalance_ratio:.2f}")
else:
    print(f"Column '{column}' has balanced data. Imbalance ratio: {imbalance_ratio:.2f}")

Column 'price_range' has balanced data. Imbalance ratio: 1.00

There seems no imbalanced data in the dataset¶

Scaling¶

In [83]:
sc = StandardScaler()
x = df.drop('price_range', axis = 1)
y = df['price_range']
x_train, x_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(x, y, test_size = 0.25, random_state = 11)
x_train = sc.fit_transform(x_train)
x_test = sc.transform(x_test)
